---
import ToolLayout from '../../layouts/ToolLayout.astro';
const title = 'Paver Sand Calculator';
const description = 'Find how much bedding sand and polymeric jointing sand you need for a paver patio or walkway, from its area and bedding depth.';
const intro = 'Find how much bedding sand and jointing sand you need under and between pavers.';
const category = { id: 'construction', name: 'Construction & Home Improvement', emoji: '🏠' };
const faqs = [
  { q: 'How much sand do I need under pavers?', a: 'Multiply the paver area by the bedding sand depth (typically 1 inch, or 1/12 foot) to get the volume. A 200 sq ft patio with a 1-inch sand bed: 200 × (1/12) = 16.7 cubic feet, about 0.6 cubic yards.' },
  { q: 'What is the difference between bedding sand and jointing sand?', a: 'Bedding sand is a thicker layer, usually about 1 inch, spread and screeded flat under the pavers to set them level. Jointing sand (often polymeric sand) is swept into the narrow gaps between the pavers after they\'re laid, locking them together and resisting weed growth and ant intrusion.' },
  { q: 'How much jointing sand do I need?', a: 'Jointing sand is estimated from the paver area and the size of the gaps between pavers; a common rule of thumb is roughly 0.5 to 1 pound of polymeric sand per square foot for standard 1/8 to 3/16 inch joints, though wider joints need more. Follow the sand manufacturer\'s coverage chart for exact quantities with your specific paver and joint size.' },
  { q: 'Do I need both a gravel base and sand bedding?', a: 'Yes, for a proper paver installation. A compacted gravel base (usually 4-6 inches) provides structural support and drainage, while the thinner sand bedding layer on top gives a fine, level surface to set the pavers into — the two layers serve different purposes and neither replaces the other.' },
];
const howTo = {
  name: 'How to calculate paver bedding and jointing sand',
  steps: [
    { name: 'Measure the area', text: 'Total paver area in square feet.' },
    { name: 'Set bedding depth', text: 'Usually 1 inch, screeded flat.' },
    { name: 'Pick joint width', text: 'Get the jointing sand estimate to match.' },
  ],
};
---

<ToolLayout title={title} description={description} intro={intro} category={category} faqs={faqs} howTo={howTo}>
  <div class="mt-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4 shadow-sm sm:p-6">
    <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
      <label class="block"><span class="text-sm font-medium text-slate-700">Paver area (sq ft)</span>
        <input id="area" type="number" step="any" placeholder="200" class="mt-1 w-full rounded-xl border border-slate-300 p-3 outline-none focus:border-indigo-400 focus:ring-2 focus:ring-indigo-100" /></label>
      <label class="block"><span class="text-sm font-medium text-slate-700">Bedding sand depth (in)</span>
        <input id="depth" type="number" step="any" placeholder="1" class="mt-1 w-full rounded-xl border border-slate-300 p-3 outline-none focus:border-indigo-400 focus:ring-2 focus:ring-indigo-100" /></label>
      <label class="block"><span class="text-sm font-medium text-slate-700">Joint width</span>
        <select id="joint" class="mt-1 w-full rounded-xl border border-slate-300 p-3 outline-none focus:border-indigo-400 focus:ring-2 focus:ring-indigo-100">
          <option value="0.6" selected>Narrow (1/8-3/16 in, ~0.6 lb/ft²)</option>
          <option value="1.0">Wide (1/4-3/8 in, ~1.0 lb/ft²)</option>
        </select></label>
    </div>
    <div id="results" class="mt-6 hidden space-y-3">
      <div class="rounded-xl bg-indigo-600 p-5 text-center text-white">
        <div class="text-sm opacity-80">Bedding sand needed</div>
        <div id="r-bedding" class="mt-1 text-2xl font-bold">—</div>
        <div id="r-note" class="text-sm opacity-80"></div>
      </div>
      <div class="grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="rounded-xl bg-slate-50 p-3 text-center"><div class="text-sm text-slate-500">Bedding volume</div><div id="r-vol" class="mt-1 text-lg font-bold text-slate-800">—</div></div>
        <div class="rounded-xl bg-slate-50 p-3 text-center"><div class="text-sm text-slate-500">Jointing sand</div><div id="r-joint" class="mt-1 text-lg font-bold text-slate-800">—</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <figure class="mt-10">
    <svg width="800" height="200" viewBox="0 0 800 200" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" role="img" aria-labelledby="ps-title ps-desc">
      <title id="ps-title">Paver, bedding sand, and gravel base cross-section</title>
      <desc id="ps-desc">A layered cross-section of pavers, bedding sand, and gravel base</desc>
      <g stroke="#78716c" stroke-width="1">
        <rect x="80" y="90" width="50" height="18" fill="#d6d3d1" /><rect x="130" y="90" width="50" height="18" fill="#e7e5e4" /><rect x="180" y="90" width="50" height="18" fill="#d6d3d1" /><rect x="230" y="90" width="50" height="18" fill="#e7e5e4" />
      </g>
      <rect x="80" y="108" width="200" height="14" fill="#fde68a" stroke="#d97706" stroke-width="1" />
      <rect x="80" y="122" width="200" height="30" fill="#94a3b8" stroke="#64748b" stroke-width="1" />
      <text x="290" y="118" font-size="11" fill="#475569" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">bedding sand</text>
      <text x="290" y="140" font-size="11" fill="#475569" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">gravel base</text>
      <rect x="420" y="55" width="330" height="110" rx="8" fill="#f8fafc" stroke="#e2e8f0" stroke-width="1" />
      <text x="440" y="84" font-size="13" font-weight="bold" fill="#1e293b" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">Sand quantities</text>
      <text x="440" y="110" font-size="12" fill="#475569" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">bedding = area &times; (depth&frasl;12) &divide; 27</text>
      <text x="440" y="132" font-size="12" fill="#475569" font-family="system-ui,sans-serif">jointing (lb) = area &times; lb&frasl;ft&sup2;</text>
    </svg>
    <figcaption class="mt-2 text-center text-sm text-slate-500">Bedding sand sets the pavers level; jointing sand locks them together at the seams.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">How the paver sand calculator works</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">
      A paver installation uses two different sand layers that serve different jobs. Bedding sand is a thicker layer, typically 1 inch deep, spread and screeded dead flat over the compacted gravel base — it's what the pavers actually rest in and get leveled into, so it needs to be uniform in depth across the whole patio or walkway. Finding how much you need is simple volume math: paver area times the bedding depth in feet, converted to cubic yards for ordering bulk sand.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600">
      Jointing sand is different — it's swept into the narrow gaps between the laid pavers, not spread as a layer underneath. Polymeric jointing sand, which hardens slightly when wetted to lock the joints and resist weeds and ant intrusion, is sold by weight, and coverage depends on the joint width: narrower 1/8 to 3/16 inch joints use roughly 0.6 pounds per square foot, while wider 1/4 to 3/8 inch joints need closer to 1 pound per square foot.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600">
      Neither sand layer replaces the compacted gravel base underneath — that base, typically 4 to 6 inches of crushed stone, provides the structural support and drainage a paver surface needs to resist settling and heaving over time. Always check your specific sand product's coverage chart for the exact rate at your paver's actual joint width, since manufacturer figures vary somewhat.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-slate-400">Bedding depth and base thickness recommendations follow ICPI (Interlocking Concrete Pavement Institute) installation guidelines; polymeric sand coverage rates are based on typical manufacturer charts (e.g. Techniseal, Alliance Gator).</p>
    <div class="mt-4 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4 text-center">
        <span class="inline-flex h-10 w-10 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-indigo-100 text-lg font-bold text-indigo-700">1</span>
        <h3 class="mt-3 font-semibold text-slate-900">Measure the area</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Total paver area in square feet.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4 text-center">
        <span class="inline-flex h-10 w-10 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-indigo-100 text-lg font-bold text-indigo-700">2</span>
        <h3 class="mt-3 font-semibold text-slate-900">Set bedding depth</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Usually 1 inch, screeded flat.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4 text-center">
        <span class="inline-flex h-10 w-10 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-indigo-100 text-lg font-bold text-indigo-700">3</span>
        <h3 class="mt-3 font-semibold text-slate-900">Pick joint width</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Get the jointing sand estimate to match.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">The formula explained</h2>
    <div class="mt-3 space-y-3">
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4">
        <p class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Bedding volume</p>
        <p class="mt-1 text-slate-600">
          <span class="font-mono">= area &times; (depth&frasl;12) &divide; 27</span>. A 200 ft² patio, 1 in deep: 200 × (1/12) ÷ 27 = <strong>0.62 yd³</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4">
        <p class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Jointing sand</p>
        <p class="mt-1 text-slate-600">
          <span class="font-mono">= area &times; lb&frasl;ft&sup2;</span>. At 0.6 lb/ft² (narrow joints): 200 × 0.6 = <strong>120 lb</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4">
        <p class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Wide joints</p>
        <p class="mt-1 text-slate-600">
          Same 200 ft² at 1.0 lb/ft²: <strong>200 lb</strong> of jointing sand.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="mt-5 rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-5">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Worked example</h3>
      <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">A 350 sq ft patio, 1.5 in bedding depth, wide joints.</p>
      <div class="mt-2 grid gap-1 text-sm sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Bedding ft³:</span> <span class="text-slate-600">350 × (1.5/12) = 43.75 ft³</span></div>
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Bedding yd³:</span> <span class="text-slate-600">43.75 ÷ 27 = <strong>1.62 yd³</strong></span></div>
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Jointing:</span> <span class="text-slate-600">350 × 1.0 = <strong>350 lb</strong></span></div>
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Bags (est.):</span> <span class="text-slate-600">7 bags of 50 lb polymeric sand</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="mt-5 text-slate-600">
      Sand type matters as much as quantity. Bedding sand should be coarse, washed concrete sand (sometimes called C-33 sand) rather than fine masonry or play sand, since coarse sand compacts and drains more predictably under load. Jointing sand is a separate product entirely — polymeric sand blends fine sand with a water-activated binder, and it should never be substituted with plain bedding sand, since it needs to stay in place under foot traffic and resist washing out during rain.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Real-world context</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">
      A backyard patio project is the most common use case. A 150 sq ft patio with a standard 1-inch bedding depth and narrow joints needs 150 × (1/12) = 12.5 cubic feet of bedding sand (about 0.46 cubic yards) plus 150 × 0.6 = 90 lb of polymeric jointing sand — roughly two 50 lb bags of jointing sand once you round up for spillage and joint variation.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600">
      A narrow front walkway scales down proportionally. At 60 sq ft with the same 1-inch bedding and narrow joints, that's 60 × (1/12) = 5 cubic feet of bedding sand (0.19 cubic yards) and 60 × 0.6 = 36 lb of jointing sand — small enough that many suppliers sell bedding sand by the bag rather than requiring a bulk delivery for a job this size.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600">
      Larger paver driveways push into bulk-delivery territory. A 600 sq ft driveway laid 1.5 inches deep with wider joints needs 600 × (1.5/12) = 75 cubic feet of bedding sand, or 2.78 cubic yards, plus 600 × 1.0 = 600 lb of jointing sand — at that volume, ordering bulk bedding sand by the yard from a landscape supplier is typically cheaper than buying dozens of individual bags.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Common misconceptions</h2>
    <div class="mt-3 space-y-3">
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4">
        <p class="text-slate-600">"More bedding sand under the pavers means a stronger, more stable patio." <strong class="text-slate-900">Not the case.</strong> Bedding sand's job is to provide a thin, level cushion for setting the pavers, not structural support — a bed thicker than about 1 to 1.5 inches actually makes the surface less stable, since the pavers can shift or settle unevenly within a deeper, looser layer. Structural support comes from the compacted gravel base underneath.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4">
        <p class="text-slate-600">"Regular play sand works fine for jointing between pavers." <strong class="text-slate-900">It doesn't hold up.</strong> Plain sand washes out of the joints with rain and gets displaced by foot traffic, letting weeds take root and ants tunnel in within a season or two. Polymeric sand contains a binder that activates when wetted, locking it in place — it costs more per bag but avoids re-sanding the joints every year.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Related calculators</h2>
    <div class="mt-3 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/tools/paver-calculator" class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-slate-700 transition hover:border-indigo-300 hover:bg-indigo-50">Paver Calculator</a>
      <a href="/tools/gravel-sand-calculator" class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-slate-700 transition hover:border-indigo-300 hover:bg-indigo-50">Gravel &amp; Sand Calculator</a>
      <a href="/tools/road-base-calculator" class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-slate-700 transition hover:border-indigo-300 hover:bg-indigo-50">Road Base Calculator</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <script is:inline>
    const el = (id) => document.getElementById(id);

    function update() {
      const area = parseFloat(el('area').value);
      const depth = parseFloat(el('depth').value);
      const jointRate = parseFloat(el('joint').value);
      if (!(area > 0 && depth > 0)) { el('results').classList.add('hidden'); return; }
      const cf = area * (depth / 12);
      const cy = cf / 27;
      const jointLb = area * jointRate;

      el('r-bedding').textContent = cy.toFixed(2) + ' yd³';
      el('r-note').textContent = area + ' ft² at ' + depth + ' in deep';
      el('r-vol').textContent = cf.toFixed(1) + ' ft³';
      el('r-joint').textContent = jointLb.toFixed(0) + ' lb';
      el('results').classList.remove('hidden');
    }

    ['area', 'depth'].forEach((id) => el(id).addEventListener('input', update));
    el('joint').addEventListener('change', update);
  </script>
</ToolLayout>
